# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iso-15926
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data modeling is a process used to define and analyze data requirements needed to support the business processes within the scope of corresponding information systems in organizations.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Therefore, the process of data modeling involves professional data modelers working closely with business stakeholders, as well as potential users of the information system.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] There are three different types of data models produced while progressing from requirements to the actual database to be used for the information system.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The data requirements are initially recorded as a conceptual data model which is essentially a set of technology independent specifications about the data and is used to discuss initial requirements with the business stakeholders.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The conceptual model is then translated into a logical data model, which documents structures of the data that can be implemented in databases.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Implementation of one conceptual data model may require multiple logical data models.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The last step in data modeling is transforming the logical data model to a physical data model that organizes the data into tables, and accounts for access, performance and storage details.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data modeling defines not just data elements, but also their structures and the relationships between them.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data modeling techniques and methodologies are used to model data in a standard, consistent, predictable manner in order to manage it as a resource.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data modelling may be performed during various types of projects and in multiple phases of projects.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data models are progressive; there is no such thing as the final data model for a business or application.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Instead, a data model should be considered a living document that will change in response to a changing business.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The data models should ideally be stored in a repository so that they can be retrieved, expanded, and edited over time.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data modelling is also used as a technique for detailing business requirements for specific databases.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] It is sometimes called *database modelling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data models provide a framework for data to be used within information systems by providing specific definitions and formats.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] If a data model is used consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data seamlessly.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The results of this are indicated in the diagram.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] However, systems and interfaces are often expensive to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] This may occur when the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] According to ANSI, this approach allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual schema.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual schema.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent across all schemas of the same data model.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In the context of business process integration (see figure), data modeling complements business process modeling, and ultimately results in database generation.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The process of designing a database involves producing the previously described three types of schemas – conceptual, logical, and physical.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The database design documented in these schemas is converted through a Data Definition Language, which can then be used to generate a database.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] A fully attributed data model contains detailed attributes (descriptions) for every entity within it.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The term "database design" can describe many different parts of the design of an overall database system.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Principally, and most correctly, it can be thought of as the logical design of the base data structures used to store the data.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In the relational model these are the tables and views.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In an object database the entities and relationships map directly to object classes and named relationships.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] However, the term "database design" could also be used to apply to the overall process of designing, not just the base data structures, but also the forms and queries used as part of the overall database application within the Database Management System or DBMS.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In the process, system interfaces account for 25% to 70% of the development and support costs of current systems.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The primary reason for this cost is that these systems do not share a common data model.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] If data models are developed on a system by system basis, then not only is the same analysis repeated in overlapping areas, but further analysis must be performed to create the interfaces between them.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Most systems within an organization contain the same basic data, redeveloped for a specific purpose.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Data models represent information areas of interest.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Sometimes models are created in a mixture of the two methods: by considering the data needs and structure of an application and by consistently referencing a subject-area model.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In many environments, the distinction between a logical data model and a physical data model is blurred.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] In addition, some CASE tools don't make a distinction between logical and physical data models.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] There are several notations for data modeling.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The actual model is frequently called "entity–relationship model", because it depicts data in terms of the entities and relationships described in the data.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] An entity–relationship model (ERM) is an abstract conceptual representation of structured data.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Entity–relationship modeling is a relational schema database modeling method, used in software engineering to produce a type of conceptual data model (or semantic data model) of a system, often a relational database, and its requirements in a top-down fashion.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] These models are being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The data modeling technique can be used to describe any ontology (i.e. an overview and classifications of used terms and their relationships) for a certain universe of discourse i.e. the area of interest.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Several techniques have been developed for the design of data models.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] While these methodologies guide data modelers in their work, two different people using the same methodology will often come up with very different results.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The definition of the generic data model is similar to the definition of a natural language.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Given an extensible list of classes, this allows the classification of any individual thing and to specification of part-whole relations for any individual object.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] By standardization of an extensible list of relation types, a generic data model enables the expression of an unlimited number of kinds of facts and will approach the capabilities of natural languages.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Conventional data models, on the other hand, have a fixed and limited domain scope, because the instantiation (usage) of such a model only allows expressions of kinds of facts that are predefined in the model.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The logical data structure of a DBMS, whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] That is unless the semantic data model is implemented in the database on purpose, a choice which may slightly impact performance but generally vastly improves productivity.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] As illustrated in the figure the real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., is symbolically defined by its description within physical data stores.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] A semantic data model is an abstraction which defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The purpose of semantic data modeling is to create a structural model of a piece of the real world, called "universe of discourse".
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The overall goal of semantic data models is to capture more meaning of data by integrating relational concepts with more powerful abstraction concepts known from the artificial intelligence field.
[src:iso-15926/data-modeling] The idea is to provide high-level modeling primitives as integral parts of a data model in order to facilitate the representation of real-world situations.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Types of interoperability include **syntactic interoperability**, where two systems can communicate with each other, and cross-domain interoperability, where multiple organizations work together and exchange information.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] If two or more systems use common data formats and communication protocols, then they are capable of communicating with each other, and they exhibit *syntactic interoperability*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] XML and SQL are examples of common data formats and protocols.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Low-level data formats also contribute to syntactic interoperability, ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Beyond the ability of two or more computer systems to exchange information, semantic interoperability is the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results as defined by the end users of both systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] To achieve semantic interoperability, both sides must refer to a common information exchange reference model.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The content of the information exchange requests are unambiguously defined: what is sent is the same as what is understood.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Cross-domain interoperability involves multiple social, organizational, political, legal entities working together for a common interest or information exchange.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability implies exchanges between a range of products, or similar products from several different vendors, or even between past and future revisions of the same product.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability may be developed *post-facto*, as a special measure between two products, while excluding the rest, by using open standards.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] When a vendor is forced to adapt its system to a dominant system that is not based on open standards, it is compatibility, not interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Open standards rely on a broadly consultative and inclusive group, including representatives from vendors, academics and others holding a stake in the development that discusses and debates the technical and economic merits, demerits and feasibility of a proposed common protocol.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] After the doubts and reservations of all members are addressed, the resulting common document is endorsed as a *common standard*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This document may be subsequently released to the public, and henceforth becomes an *open standard*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] It is usually published and is available freely or at a nominal cost to any and all comers, with *no further encumbrances*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The vendors' products compete on the quality of their implementation, user interface, ease of use, performance, price, and a host of other factors, while keeping the customer's data intact and transferable even if they choose to switch to another competing product for business reasons.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] However, while "open" is a necessary condition for an interoperabilty standard, it is not a sufficient condition.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] For example, the standard-setting processes for the Fortran, C, and C++ languages are open, with a broadly-inclusive consultative group.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] But the resulting standards are not interoperability standards.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The data itself may be encumbered, e.g., by patents or pricing, leading to a dependence of all competing solutions on the original vendor, and possibly leading to a revenue stream from the competitors' customers back to the original vendor.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This revenue stream is the result of the original product's market dominance and not a result of any innate superiority.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Alternatively, it can be argued that even open processes are subject to the weight of past implementations and imperfect past designs and that the power of the dominant vendor to unilaterally correct or improve the system and impose the changes to all users facilitates innovation.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Lack of an open standard can also become problematic for the customers, as in the case of the original vendor's inability to fix a certain problem that is an artifact of technical limitations in the original product.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Speaking from an e-government perspective, interoperability refers to the collaboration ability of cross-border services for citizens, businesses and public administrations.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Exchanging data can be a challenge due to language barriers, different specifications of formats, varieties of categorizations and other hindrances.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] If data is interpreted differently, collaboration is limited, takes longer and is inefficient.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] For instance, if a citizen of country A wants to purchase land in country B, the person will be asked to submit the proper address data.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Address data in both countries includes full name details, street name and number, as well as a postal code.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The order of the address details might vary.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In the same language, it is not an obstacle to order the provided address data, but across language barriers, it becomes difficult.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] If the language uses a different writing system it is almost impossible if no translation tools are available.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability is used by researchers in the context of urban flood risk management.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Cities and urban areas worldwide are expanding, which creates complex spaces with many interactions between the environment, infrastructure and people.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] To address this complexity and manage water in urban areas appropriately, a system of systems approach to water and flood control is necessary.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At the strategic level, interoperability is an enabler for coalition building.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] It facilitates meaningful contributions by coalition partners.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At this level, interoperability issues center on harmonizing world views, strategies, doctrines, and force structures.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability is an element of coalition willingness to work together over the long term to achieve and maintain shared interests against common threats.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability at the operational and tactical levels is where strategic interoperability and technological interoperability come together to help allies shape the environment, manage crises, and win wars.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The benefits of interoperability at the operational and tactical levels generally derive from the interchangeability of force elements and units.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] *Technological interoperability* reflects the interfaces between organizations and systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] It focuses on communications and computers but also involves the technical capabilities of systems and the resulting mission compatibility between the systems and data of coalition partners.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At the technological level, the benefits of interoperability come primarily from their impacts at the operational and tactical levels in terms of enhancing flexibility.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Because first responders need to be able to communicate during wide-scale emergencies, interoperability is an important issue for law enforcement, firefighting, emergency medical services, and other public health and safety departments.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] It has been a major area of investment and research over the last 12 years.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Widely disparate and incompatible hardware impedes the exchange of information between agencies.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Agencies' information systems, such as computer-aided dispatch systems and records management systems, functioned largely in isolation, in so-called *information islands*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Agencies tried to bridge this isolation with inefficient, stopgap methods while large agencies began implementing limited interoperable systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] These approaches were inadequate and, in the US, the lack of interoperability in the public safety realm became evident during the 9/11 attacks on the Pentagon and World Trade Center structures.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Further evidence of a lack of interoperability surfaced when agencies tackled the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In contrast to the overall national picture, some states, including Utah, have already made great strides forward.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The Utah Highway Patrol and other departments in Utah have created a statewide data sharing network.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The Commonwealth of Virginia is one of the leading states in the United States in improving interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The Interoperability Coordinator leverages a regional structure to better allocate grant funding around the Commonwealth so that all areas have an opportunity to improve communications interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The State of Washington seeks to enhance interoperability statewide.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Washington recognizes that collaborating on system design and development for wireless radio systems enables emergency responder agencies to efficiently provide additional services, increase interoperability, and reduce long-term costs.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This work saves the lives of emergency personnel and the citizens they serve.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The U.S. government is making an effort to overcome the nation's lack of public safety interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The Department of Homeland Security's Office for Interoperability and Compatibility (OIC) is pursuing the SAFECOM and CADIP and Project 25 programs, which are designed to help agencies as they integrate their CAD and other IT systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This project will partner the OIC with agencies in several locations, including Silicon Valley.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This program will use case studies to identify the best practices and challenges associated with linking CAD systems across jurisdictional boundaries.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] These lessons will create the tools and resources public safety agencies can use to build interoperable CAD systems and communicate across local, state, and federal boundaries.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Governance entities can increase interoperability through their legislative and executive powers.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Conversely, government-mandated interoperability has been heavily criticized as leading to monopolies that become too big to fail.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] For example, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission's implementation of 1975 amendments to the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that were intended to ensure interoperability was blamed for driving all regional clearinghouses and depositories out of business in the United States.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] As a result, the National Securities Clearing Corporation is the sole clearinghouse; the Depository Trust Company is the sole repository; and their parent, the Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation, has enormous market power over central counterparty clearing in the United States.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In contrast, the federal government of the United States did not attempt to mandate or regulate credit card interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This allowed credit card networks to naturally develop interoperability (in the sense that almost every payment terminal can automatically accept almost every credit card), so that Visa Inc. was not left as the last credit card network standing.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Desktop interoperability is a subset of software interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In the early days, the focus of interoperability was to integrate web applications with other web applications.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Over time, open-system containers were developed to create a virtual desktop environment in which these applications could be registered and then communicate with each other using simple publish–subscribe patterns.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Rudimentary UI capabilities were also supported, allowing windows to be grouped with other windows.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Today, desktop interoperability has evolved into full-service platforms that include container support, basic exchange between web and web, but also native support for other application types and advanced window management.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The very latest interop platforms also include application services such as universal search, notifications, user permissions and preferences, 3rd party application connectors and language adapters for in-house applications.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Search interoperability refers to the ability of two or more information collections to be searched by a single query.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Specifically related to web-based search, the challenge of interoperability stems from the fact that designers of web resources typically have little or no need to concern themselves with exchanging information with other web resources.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Federated Search technology, which does not place format requirements on the data owner, has emerged as one solution to search interoperability challenges.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In addition, standards, such as Open Archives Initiative Protocol for Metadata Harvesting, Resource Description Framework, and SPARQL, have emerged that also help address the issue of search interoperability related to web resources.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Such standards also address broader topics of interoperability, such as allowing data mining.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] With respect to software, the term *interoperability* is used to describe the capability of different programs to exchange data via a common set of exchange formats, to read and write the same file formats, and to use the same communication protocols.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The lack of interoperability can be a consequence of a lack of attention to standardization during the design of a program.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Indeed, interoperability is not taken for granted in the non-standards-based portion of the computing world.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Standards-developing organizations provide open public software specifications to facilitate interoperability; examples include the Oasis-Open organization and buildingSMART (formerly the International Alliance for Interoperability).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Another example of a neutral party is the RFC documents from the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The Open Service for Lifecycle Collaboration community is working on finding a common standard in order that software tools can share and exchange data e.g., bugs, tasks, requirements etc.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The final goal is to agree on an open standard for interoperability of open source application lifecycle management tools.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Java is an example of an interoperable programming language that allows for programs to be written once and run anywhere with a Java virtual machine.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] A program in Java, so long as it does not use system-specific functionality, will maintain interoperability with all systems that have a Java virtual machine available.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Applications will maintain compatibility because, while the implementation is different, the underlying language interfaces are the same.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Product engineering Implements the common standard, or a sub-profile thereof, as defined by the industry and community partnerships with the specific intention of achieving interoperability with other software implementations, also following the same standard or sub-profile thereof.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Industry and community partnership Industry and community partnerships, either domestic or international, sponsor standard workgroups with the purpose of defining a common standard that may be used to allow software systems to intercommunicate for a defined purpose.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At times, an industry or community will sub-profile an existing standard produced by another organization to reduce options and thus make interoperability more achievable for implementations.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] This technique has some of the same technical results as using a common vendor product to produce interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The common technology can come through third-party libraries or open-source developments.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Standard implementation Software interoperability requires a common agreement that is normally arrived at via an industrial, national or international standard.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Each of these has an important role in reducing variability in intercommunication software and enhancing a common understanding of the end goal to be achieved.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Language interoperability is the capability of two different programming languages to natively interact as part of the same system and operate on the same kind of data structures.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] There are many ways programming languages are interoperable with one another.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are interoperable as they are used in tandem in webpages.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Some object oriented languages are interoperable thanks to their shared hosting virtual machine (e.g. .NET CLI compliant languages in the Common Language Runtime and JVM compliant languages in the Java Virtual Machine).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Unified interoperability is the property of a system that allows for the integration of real-time and non-real time communications, activities, data, and information services (i.e., unified) and the display and coordination of those services across systems and devices (i.e., interoperability).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Unified interoperability provides the capability to communicate and exchange processing across different applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability tends to be regarded as an issue for experts and its implications for daily living are sometimes underrated.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The European Union Microsoft competition case shows how interoperability concerns important questions of power relationships.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In 2004, the European Commission found that Microsoft had abused its market power by deliberately restricting interoperability between Windows Workgroup servers and non-Microsoft work group servers.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] By doing so, Microsoft was able to protect its dominant market position for work group server operating systems, the heart of corporate IT networks.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Microsoft was ordered to disclose complete and accurate interface documentation, which could enable rival vendors to compete on an equal footing (*the interoperability remedy*).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability has also surfaced in the software patent debate in the European Parliament (June–July 2005).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability is often more of an organizational issue.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability can have a significant impact on the organizations concerned, raising issues of ownership (do people want to share their data? or are they dealing with information silos?), labor relations (are people prepared to undergo training?) and usability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In this context, a more apt definition is captured in the term *business process interoperability*.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Interoperability can have important economic consequences; for example, research has estimated the cost of inadequate interoperability in the US capital facilities industry to be $15.8 billion a year.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] If competitors' products are not interoperable (due to causes such as patents, trade secrets or coordination failures), the result may well be monopoly or market failure.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] For this reason, it may be prudent for user communities or governments to take steps to encourage interoperability in various situations.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At least 30 international bodies and countries have implemented eGovernment-based interoperability framework initiatives called e-GIF, while in the US, there is the NIEM initiative.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The need for *plug-and-play* interoperability – the ability to take a medical device out of its box and easily make it work with one's other devices – has attracted great attention from both healthcare providers and industry.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Increasingly, medical devices like incubators and imaging systems feature software that integrates at the point of care and with electronic systems, such as electronic medical records.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] At the 2016 Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society (RAPS) meeting, experts in the field like Angela N.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Johnson with GE Healthcare and Jeff Shuren of the United States Food and Drug Administration, provided practical seminars on how companies developing new medical devices, and hospitals installing them, can work more effectively to align interoperable software systems.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Railways have greater or lesser interoperability depending on conforming to standards of gauge, couplings, brakes, signalling, loading gauge, and structure gauge to mention a few parameters.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] For passenger rail service, different railway platform height and width clearance standards may also affect interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] North American freight and intercity passenger railroads are highly interoperable, but systems in Europe, Asia, Africa, Central and South America, and Australia are much less so.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The parameter most difficult to overcome (at reasonable cost) is incompatibility of gauge, though variable gauge axle systems can be used on rolling stock.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The condition achieved among communications-electronics systems or items of communications-electronics equipment when information or services can be exchanged directly and satisfactorily between them or their users.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The degree of interoperability should be defined when referring to specific cases.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Many organizations are dedicated to interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Some concentrate on eGovernment, eBusiness or data exchange in general.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] Internationally, Network Centric Operations Industry Consortium facilitates global interoperability across borders, language and technical barriers.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In the built environment, the International Alliance for Interoperability started in 1994 and was renamed buildingSMART in 2005.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In Europe, the European Commission and its IDABC program issue the European Interoperability Framework.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] IDABC was succeeded by the Interoperability Solutions for European Public Administrations (ISA) program.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] They also initiated the Semantic Interoperability Centre Europe (SEMIC.EU).
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] A European Land Information Service (EULIS) was established in 2006, as a consortium of European National Land Registers.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The aim of the service is to establish a single portal through which customers are provided with access to information about individual properties, about land and property registration services, and about the associated legal environment.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The European Interoperability Framework (EIF) considered four kinds of interoperability: legal interoperability, organizational interoperability, semantic interoperability, and technical interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In the European Research Cluster on the Internet of Things (IERC) and IoT Semantic Interoperability Best Practices; four kinds of interoperability are distinguished: syntactical interoperability, technical interoperability, semantic interoperability, and organizational interoperability.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] In the United States, the General Services Administration Component Organization and Registration Environment (CORE.GOV) initiative provided a collaboration environment for component development, sharing, registration, and reuse in the early 2000s.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] A related initiative is the ongoing National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) work and component repository.
[src:iso-15926/interoperability] The National Institute of Standards and Technology serves as an agency for measurement standards.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The title, "*Industrial automation systems and integration—Integration of life-cycle data for process plants including oil and gas production facilities*", is regarded too narrow by the present ISO 15926 developers.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Having developed a generic data model and reference data library for process plants, it turned out that this subject is already so wide, that actually any state information may be modelled with it.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In 1991 a European Union ESPRIT-, named ProcessBase, started.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The focus of this research project was to develop a data model for lifecycle information of a facility that would suit the requirements of the process industries.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] At the time that the project duration had elapsed, a consortium of companies involved in the process industries had been established: EPISTLE (European Process Industries STEP Technical Liaison Executive).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Initially individual companies were members, but later this changed into a situation where three national consortia were the only members: PISTEP (UK), POSC/Caesar (Norway), and USPI-NL (Netherlands).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] (later PISTEP merged into POSC/Caesar, and USPI-NL was renamed to USPI).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] EPISTLE took over the work of the ProcessBase project.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Initially this work involved a standard called ISO 10303-221 (referred to as "STEP AP221").
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In that AP221 we saw, for the first time, an Annex M with a list of standard instances of the AP221 data model, including types of objects.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] These standard instances would be for reference and would act as a knowledge base with knowledge about the types of objects.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In the early nineties EPISTLE started an activity to extend Annex M to become a library of such object classes and their relationships: STEPlib.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In the STEPlib activities a group of approx.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] 100 domain experts from all three member consortia, spread over the various expertises (e.g.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Electrical, Piping, Rotating equipment, etc.), worked together to define the "core classes".
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The development of STEPlib was extended with many additional classes and relationships between classes and published as Open source data.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Furthermore, the concepts and relation types from the AP221 and ISO 15926-2 data models were also added to the STEPlib dictionary.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] This resulted in the development of Gellish English, whereas STEPlib became the Gellish English dictionary.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Gellish English is a structured subset of natural English and is a modeling language suitable for knowledge modeling, product modeling and data exchange.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] It differs from conventional modeling languages (meta languages) as used in information technology as it not only defines generic concepts, but also includes an English dictionary.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The semantic expression capability of Gellish English was significantly increased by extending the number of relation types that can be used to express knowledge and information.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] For modelling-technical reasons POSC/Caesar proposed another standard than ISO 10303, called ISO 15926.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] EPISTLE (and ISO) supported that proposal, and continued the modelling work, thereby writing Part 2 of ISO 15926.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] This Part 2 has official ISO IS (International Standard) status since 2003.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] POSC/Caesar started to put together their own RDL (Reference Data Library).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] They added many specialized classes, for example for ANSI (American National Standards Institute) pipe and pipe fittings.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Meanwhile, STEPlib continued its existence, mainly driven by some members of USPI.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Since it was clear that it was not in the interest of the industry to have two libraries for, in essence, the same set of classes, the Management Board of EPISTLE decided that the core classes of the two libraries shall be merged into Part 4 of ISO 15926.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Part 4 should act as reference data for part 2 of ISO 15926 as well as for ISO 10303-221 and replaced its Annex M.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] On June 5, 2007 ISO 15926-4 was signed off as a TS (Technical Specification).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In 1999 the work on an earlier version of Part 7 started.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Initially this was based on XML Schema (the only useful W3C Recommendation available then), but when Web Ontology Language (OWL) became available it was clear that provided a far more suitable environment for Part 7.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Part 7 passed the first ISO ballot by the end of 2005, and an implementation project started.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] A formal ballot for TS (Technical Specification) was planned for December 2007.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] However, it was decided then to split Part 7 into more than one part, because the scope was too wide.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In 2004, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) released a report on the impact of the lack of digital interoperability in the capital projects industry.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The report estimated the cost of inadequate interoperability in the U.S. capital facilities industry to be $15.8 billion per year.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] This was considered likely to be a conservative figure.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The model and the library are suitable for representing lifecycle information about technical installations and their components.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] They can also be used for defining the terms used in product catalogs in e-commerce.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Another, more limited, use of the standard is as a reference classification for harmonization purposes between shared databases and product catalogues that are not based on ISO 15926.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The purpose of ISO 15926 is to provide a Lingua Franca for computer systems, thereby integrating the information produced by them.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Although set up for the process industries with large projects involving many parties, and involving plant operations and maintenance lasting decades, the technology can be used by anyone willing to set up a proper vocabulary of reference data in line with Part 4.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In Part 7 the concept of Templates is introduced.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] These are semantic constructs, using Part 2 entities, that represent a small piece of information.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] These constructs then are mapped to more efficient classes of n-ary relations that interlink the Nodes that are involved in the represented information.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In Part 8 the Part 7 Templates are defined in OWL and instantiated in RDF.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] For validation and reasoning purposes all are represented in First-Order Logic as well.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In Part 9 these Node and Template instances are stored in an RDF triple store, set up to a standard schema and an API.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Each participating computer system maps its data from its internal format to such ISO-standard Node and Template instances.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Data can be "handed over" from one triple store to another in cases where data custodianship is handed over (e.g. from a contractor to a plant owner, or from a manufacturer to the owners of the manufactured goods).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Hand-over can be for a part of all data, whilst maintaining full referential integrity.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] They are defined in XML Schema and they are, in essence, only a structure containing cells that make reference to instances of Templates.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] This represents a view on all lifecycle data: since the data model is a 4D (space-time) model, it is possible to present the data that was valid at any given point in time, thus providing a true historical record.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] It is expected that this will be used for Knowledge Mining.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] In any implementation a restricted number of triple stores can be involved, with different access rights.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] This is done by means of creating a CPF Server (= Confederation of Participating Façades).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] An Ontology Browser allows for access to one or more triple stores in a given CPF, depending on the access rights.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] There are a number of projects working on the extension of the ISO 15926 standard in different application areas.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The Norwegian Oil Industry Association (OLF) has decided to use ISO 15926 (also known as the Oil and Gas Ontology) as the instrument for integrating data across disciplines and business domains for the Upstream Oil and Gas industry.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] It is seen as one of the enablers of what has been called the next (or second) generation of Integrated operations, where a better integration across companies is the goal.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] One of the main requirements was (and still is) that the scope of the data model covers the entire lifecycle of a facility (e.g. oil refinery) and its components (e.g. pipes, pumps and their parts, etc.).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Since such a facility over such a long time entails many different types of activities on a myriad of different objects it became clear that a generic and data-driven data model would be required.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] There are thousands of different types of physical objects in a facility (pumps, compressors, pipes, instruments, fluids, etc).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] If all combinations would be modelled in a "hard-coded" fashion, the number of combinations would be staggering, and unmanageable.
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] The solution is a "template" that represents the semantics of: "This object has a property of X yyyy" (where yyyy is the unit of measure).
[src:iso-15926/iso-15926] Without being able to make reference to those classes, via the Internet, it will be impossible to express this information.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] In information science, an **ontology** encompasses a representation, formal naming, and definitions of the categories, properties, and relations between the concepts, data, or entities that pertain to one, many, or all domains of discourse.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] More simply, an ontology is a way of showing the properties of a subject area and how they are related, by defining a set of terms and relational expressions that represent the entities in that subject area.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The field which studies ontologies so conceived is sometimes referred to as *applied ontology*.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Every academic discipline or field, in creating its terminology, thereby lays the groundwork for an ontology.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Each uses ontological assumptions to frame explicit theories, research and applications.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Improved ontologies may improve problem solving within that domain, interoperability of data systems, and discoverability of data.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Translating research papers within every field is a problem made easier when experts from different countries maintain a controlled vocabulary of jargon between each of their languages.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] For instance, the definition and ontology of economics is a primary concern in Marxist economics, but also in other subfields of economics.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] An example of economics relying on information science occurs in cases where a simulation or model is intended to enable economic decisions, such as determining what capital assets are at risk and by how much (see risk management).
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] What ontologies in both information science and philosophy have in common is the attempt to represent entities, including both objects and events, with all their interdependent properties and relations, according to a system of categories.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Applied ontology is considered by some as a successor to prior work in philosophy.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Artificial intelligence has retained considerable attention regarding applied ontology in subfields like natural language processing within machine translation and knowledge representation, but ontology editors are being used often in a range of fields, including biomedical informatics and industry.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Such efforts often use ontology editing tools such as Protégé.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Ontology is a branch of philosophy and intersects areas such as metaphysics, epistemology, and philosophy of language, as it considers how knowledge, language, and perception relate to the nature of reality.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Metaphysics deals with questions like "what exists?" and "what is the nature of reality?".
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] One of five traditional branches of philosophy, metaphysics is concerned with exploring existence through properties, entities and relations such as those between particulars and universals, intrinsic and extrinsic properties, or essence and existence.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Metaphysics has been an ongoing topic of discussion since recorded history.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The compound word *ontology* combines *onto-*, from the Greek ὄν, *on* (gen. ὄντος, *ontos*), i.e.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] "being; that which is", which is the present participle of the verb εἰμί, *eimí*, i.e.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] "logical discourse", see classical compounds for this type of word formation.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] While the etymology is Greek, the oldest extant record of the word itself, the Neo-Latin form *ontologia*, appeared in 1606 in the work *Ogdoas Scholastica* by Jacob Lorhard (*Lorhardus*) and in 1613 in the *Lexicon philosophicum* by Rudolf Göckel (*Goclenius*).
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The first occurrence in English of *ontology* as recorded by the *OED* (*Oxford English Dictionary*, online edition, 2008) came in *Archeologia Philosophica Nova* or *New Principles of Philosophy* (1663) by Gideon Harvey.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Since the mid-1970s, researchers in the field of artificial intelligence (AI) have recognized that knowledge engineering is the key to building large and powerful AI systems.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] AI researchers argued that they could create new ontologies as computational models that enable certain kinds of automated reasoning, which was only marginally successful.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] In the 1980s, the AI community began to use the term *ontology* to refer to both a theory of a modeled world and a component of knowledge-based systems.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Some researchers, drawing inspiration from philosophical ontologies, viewed computational ontology as a kind of applied philosophy.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] In 1993, the widely cited web page and paper "Toward Principles for the Design of Ontologies Used for Knowledge Sharing" by Tom Gruber used *ontology* as a technical term in computer science closely related to earlier idea of semantic networks and taxonomies.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Though not yet widely adopted in academic discourse, such models propose phased approaches to ethical harmonization and structural emergence.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Contemporary ontologies share many structural similarities, regardless of the language in which they are expressed.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Most ontologies describe individuals (instances), classes (concepts), attributes and relations.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] A domain ontology (or domain-specific ontology) represents concepts which belong to a realm of the world, such as biology or politics.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Each domain ontology typically models domain-specific definitions of terms.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] For example, the word *card* has many different meanings.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] An ontology about the domain of poker would model the "playing card" meaning of the word, while an ontology about the domain of computer hardware would model the "punched card" and "video card" meanings.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Since domain ontologies are written by different people, they represent concepts in very specific and unique ways, and are often incompatible within the same project.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] As systems that rely on domain ontologies expand, they often need to merge domain ontologies by hand-tuning each entity or using a combination of software merging and hand-tuning.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] This presents a challenge to the ontology designer.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Different ontologies in the same domain arise due to different languages, different intended usage of the ontologies, and different perceptions of the domain (based on cultural background, education, ideology, etc.).
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] At present, merging ontologies that are not developed from a common upper ontology is a largely manual process and therefore time-consuming and expensive.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Domain ontologies that use the same upper ontology to provide a set of basic elements with which to specify the meanings of the domain ontology entities can be merged with less effort.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] There are studies on generalized techniques for merging ontologies, but this area of research is still ongoing, and it is a recent event to see the issue sidestepped by having multiple domain ontologies using the same upper ontology like the OBO Foundry.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] An upper ontology (or foundation ontology) is a model of the commonly shared relations and objects that are generally applicable across a wide range of domain ontologies.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] It usually employs a core glossary that overarches the terms and associated object descriptions as they are used in various relevant domain ontologies.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Standardized upper ontologies available for use include BFO, Dublin Core, GFO, Cyc, SUMO, UMBEL, and DOLCE.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] WordNet has been considered an upper ontology by some and has been used as a linguistic tool for learning domain ontologies.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The Gellish ontology is an example of a combination of an upper and a domain ontology.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] A survey of ontology visualization methods is presented by Katifori et al.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] An updated survey of ontology visualization methods and tools was published by Dudás et al.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The most established ontology visualization methods, namely indented tree and graph visualization are evaluated by Fu et al.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] A visual language for ontologies represented in OWL is specified by the *Visual Notation for OWL Ontologies (VOWL)*.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Ontology engineering (also called ontology building) is a set of tasks related to the development of ontologies for a particular domain.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] It is a subfield of knowledge engineering that studies the ontology development process, the ontology life cycle, the methods and methodologies for building ontologies, and the tools and languages that support them.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Ontology engineering aims to make explicit the knowledge contained in software applications, and organizational procedures for a particular domain.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Ontology engineering offers a direction for overcoming semantic obstacles, such as those related to the definitions of business terms and software classes.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Ontology learning is the automatic or semi-automatic creation of ontologies, including extracting a domain's terms from natural language text.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] As building ontologies manually is extremely labor-intensive and time-consuming, there is great motivation to automate the process.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Information extraction and text mining have been explored to automatically link ontologies to documents, for example in the context of the BioCreative challenges.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Epistemological assumptions, which in research asks "What do you know? or "How do you know it?", creates the foundation researchers use when approaching a certain topic or area for potential research.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] As epistemology is directly linked to knowledge and how we come about accepting certain truths, individuals conducting academic research must understand what allows them to begin theory building.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] Simply, epistemological assumptions force researchers to question how they arrive at the knowledge they have.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] An ontology language is a formal language used to encode an ontology.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The W3C Linking Open Data community project coordinates attempts to converge different ontologies into worldwide Semantic Web.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The development of ontologies has led to the emergence of services providing lists or directories of ontologies called ontology libraries.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The following are libraries of human-selected ontologies.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] The following are both directories and search engines.
[src:iso-15926/ontology-information-science] In general, ontologies can be used beneficially in several fields.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] An **oil production plant** is a facility which processes production fluids from oil wells in order to separate out key components and prepare them for export.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Typical oil well production fluids are a mixture of oil, gas and produced water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] An oil production plant is distinct from an oil depot, which does not have processing facilities.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Oil production plant may be associated with onshore or offshore oil fields.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Many permanent offshore installations have full oil production facilities.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Smaller platforms and subsea wells export production fluids to the nearest production facility, which may be on a nearby offshore processing installation or an onshore terminal.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The produced oil may sometimes be *stabilised* (a form of distillation) which reduces vapour pressure and sweetens "sour" crude oil by removing hydrogen sulphide, thereby making the crude oil suitable for storage and transport.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Offshore installations deliver oil and gas to onshore terminals which may further process the fluids prior to sale or delivery to oil refineries.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The configuration of onshore oil production facilities depends on the size of the oil field.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] For simple fields comprising a single well or a few wells, an oil storage tank may be sufficient.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The tank is emptied periodically by road tanker and transferred to an oil refinery.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] For larger production rates a rail tanker transfer facility may be appropriate.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] For larger fields a full three-phase processing facility is required.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Three-phase separators separate the well fluids into its three constituent phases: oil, gas and produced water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Oil may be transferred by road or rail tanker or by pipeline to an oil refinery.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Gas may be used on the site to run gas engines to produce electricity or can be piped to local users.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Produced water may be re-injected into the reservoir.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Small fields can use portable integrated packages, like vapor-tight tanks.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] There is a wide variety of options for the processing of produced oil.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These range from minimal offshore processing with all produced fluids sent to an onshore facility, to full offshore processing to make products to a specification suitable for sale or use with no further onshore processing.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The Gulf of Mexico and the North Sea are two mature producing areas that have taken different approaches to the facilities provided.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] In the Central and Northern North Sea gas is delivered to St Fergus or Teesside terminals by a small number of large diameter (36 inch, 91.4 cm) gas pipelines.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These operate at 1600 – 2500 psig (110 – 172 bar) in the dense phase i.e. above the critical pressure.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These advantages are offset by the additional compression required and thicker walled, more expensive, pipelines are necessary.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] A further consideration is the number of separation trains and the number of stages of separation.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Trains of process facilities operate in parallel, and stages are operated in a sequential series.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The number of trains depends on flowrates, the availability of plant, and the available plot area.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Vessel sizes can be up to 14 to 19 feet (4.3 to 5.8 m) diameter and up to 30 feet (9.1 m) long.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Vessels on Gulf of Mexico deepwater installations are 12 to 14 feet (3.7 to 4.3 m) diameter and 60 to 70 feet (18 to 21 m) long.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] First stage separators in the Gulf of Mexico typically operate at 1500 to 1800 psi (103.4 to 124.1 bar), they operate as 2-phase liquid and vapour separators with a liquid residence time of 1 to 2 minutes.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Produced water is removed in the low pressure (LP) 3-phase separator.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] In the North Sea first stage separators generally operate at < 750 psi (< 51.72 bar).
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These are operated as 3-phase (vapour, oil and water) separators and are sized to provide 3 – 5 minutes of liquid residence time.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Pressures are set to maximise gas separation at as a high a pressure as possible.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Up to 5 stages of separation are common in the Gulf of Mexico and up to 4 stages on platforms in the North Sea.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The throughput, number of trains, separation stages and first stage separator pressure for a range of historic offshore installations is shown in the table.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] A range of materials of construction are used for oil processing plant.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Carbon steel is extensively used as it is inexpensive.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] However, it is unsuitable for corrosive service where a number of corrosion resistant alloys and other materials are required.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The table illustrates typical materials for service on a plant that processes sour fluids.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The production plant can be considered to begin after the production wing valve on the oil well Christmas tree.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The reservoir fluids from each well are piped through a flowline to a choke valve, which regulates the rate of flow and reduces the pressure of the fluids.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The flowlines from each well are gathered together at one or more inlet manifolds.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These are provided for each train or operate at different pressures to match the wellhead pressure with various separator pressures.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] High pressure manifolds are routed into a first stage separator, which separates the three fluid phases.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Produced water, the densest phase, settles out at the bottom of the separator, oil floats on the top of the produced water phase, and gas occupies the upper part of the separator.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The separator is sized to provide a liquid residence time of 3 to 5 minutes which is sufficient for light crude oil (>35° API) as produced in the North Sea.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] In the Gulf of Mexico the first stage separator operates as a 2-phase (gas and liquid) vessel, it is sized to provide a liquid residence time of 1 to 2 minutes.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Sand and other solids from the reservoir will tend to settle out in the bottom of the separators.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] If allowed to accumulate the solids reduce the volume available for oil/gas/water separation reducing efficiency.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The vessel may be taken offline and drained down and the solids removed by digging out by hand.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Or water sparge pipes in the base of the separator used to fluidize the sand which can be drained from the drain valves in the base.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Oil from the first stage separator may be cooled or heated in a heat exchanger to aid further separation.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] North Sea fields tend to operate at higher temperatures so heating may not be required.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Gulf of Mexico fields tend to operate at lower temperatures so heat is required to achieve export vapor and BS&W specifications.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Oil is then routed either to a second stage separator, operating at a lower pressure than the first stage to further separate oil/gas/water, or to a coalescer to further remove water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Several stages of separation, operating at successively lower pressures, aim to reduce the amount of dissolved gas and hence reduces the flash point of the oil to meet the export oil specification.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] For higher oil flowrates parallel trains of separators may be necessary to handle the flow and to provide a turn-down capability.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The final stage of separation may be an electrostatic coalescer.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] These can achieve a 0.5% by volume water content, typical design fluxes are in the order of 200 bopd/ft2.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] A test separator (see diagram) enables the performance of individual wells to be determined.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] An individual well is connected to the test header which routes fluids to the test separator.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Three phase separation into oil, vapour and produced water takes place.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The flowrates of these phases are accurately measured as the fluids flow to lower pressure points in the oil train.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The flowrates determine the performance of the well in terms of the maximum flow of the well, the gas-oil ratio, and the water cut of the fluids.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Some oil fields are sour, with high levels of carbon dioxide (CO2) and hydrogen sulphide (H2S).
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Operation of separation at high temperature drives these gases to the vapour phase.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] However, crude may still contain sour compounds above a typical H2S-in-crude specification limit of < 10 ppmw.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] A trayed column is used with sour crude fed in the top of the column and stripping gas introduced into the bottom of the column.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] From the final stage of separation, or from the coaleser, oil may be cooled to meet export specifications or to limit thermal stresses on the oil export riser.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Oil is metered to accurately measure the flowrate and then pumped via a pipeline to the onshore terminal.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Some installations such as concrete gravity-base structures and floating production storage and offloading, FPSOs, have integral oil storage tanks which are continuously filled with oil and periodically discharged into oil tankers.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Produced water from the separator(s) and coalescer is routed to a produced water degasser operating at near atmospheric pressure to remove dissolved gas from the water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] In the early days of the offshore industry parallel plate separator units were used to clean produced water prior to overboard disposal.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Hydrocyclones, which are more compact, were introduced in the 1980s.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] A hydrocyclone removes entrained oil and solids from produced water which then passes to the degasser and can then either be re-injected into the reservoir or dumped overboard.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Induced gas flotation plant is used when the hydrocyclone / degasser plant cannot achieve the oil-in-water specification.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] For overboard disposal the water should have an oil content of less than about 30 parts per million (ppm) oil-in-water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] On North Sea installations the higher operating temperatures allow an oil-in-water concentration of > 20 ppmw to be achieved.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The associated gas from the top of the separator(s) is also known as flash gas or wet gas as it is saturated with water and liquid hydrocarbons.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The gas is typically routed through scrubbers, compressors and coolers to raise the pressure of the gas and to remove liquids.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Scrubbers are vertical vessels that allow the removal and separation of liquids from a gas stream.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Coolers are located after a compressor to remove the heat of compression.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Centrifugal compressors are often used offshore.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] They are more compact and lighter than reciprocating machines and maintenance costs are less.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The latter are used where only small volumes of gas are handled.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Centrifugal compressors may be driven by gas turbines or electric motors.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The dry gas may be exported, used for gas lift, flared, used as fuel for the installation's power generators, or after further compression re-injected into the reservoir.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Export gas is metered to accurately measure the flowrate before being sent to the onshore terminal via gas pipeline.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Other treatment processes may be required.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Gas may be dried to reduce the water content to meet sales specification, to prevent condensation of water in the pipeline and the formation of slugs, or to avoid the formation of hydrates in the export pipeline.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Gas is dried by counter-current contact with triethylene glycol in a glycol dehydration tower.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Typically dried gas has a water content of 2.5 to 7 lb of water /MMSCF.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Glycol contactors generally operate at 1100–1200 psi (75 to 83 bar).
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Water-rich glycol is regenerated by heating and stripping off the water.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Enhanced regeneration uses DRIZO or Coldfinger to improve the regeneration performance.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Contactor towers formerly comprised bubble cap trays, since the 1980s structured packing has been used which provides the equivalent of 3 to 4 theoretical trays required to meet a water content of <4 lb/MMSCF.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The export hydrocarbon dew-point specification (typically 100 barg at 5 °C) may be met by chilling the gas to remove the higher alkanes (butane, pentanes, etc.).
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] This may be done by a refrigeration system, or passing the gas through a Joule-Thomson valve, or through a turbo-expander to condense out and separate liquids.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The natural gas liquids (NGL) produced may be spiked into the oil export fluids where high vapor pressure fluids are exported.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Alternatively NGL fractionating columns may be used to produce a fluid for separate export.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] NGL fractionation columns are installed in Nkossa West Africa and Ardjuna Indonesia.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Dry gas may be further treated to meet export gas specifications.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Excess carbon dioxide (CO2) can be removed by treatment in an amine gas treating process (e.g.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Selexol), whereby CO2 is preferentially dissolved in a counter-current flow of amine in a contact tower.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Hydrogen sulphide can also be removed using amine or by passing the gas through beds of zinc oxide absorbent.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Onshore oil terminals receive oil from offshore installations and treat it to produce products for sale or further processing such as in an oil refinery.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Onshore terminals generally have fired heaters followed by separators and coalescers to stabilise the crude and remove any produced water and light hydrocarbons not separated offshore.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Onshore separators tend to operate at a lower pressure than the offshore separators and so more gas is evolved.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] The associated gas is generally compressed, dew-pointed and exported via a dedicated pipeline.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] If gas export is uneconomical then it may be flared.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Onshore terminals frequently have large crude oil storage tanks to allow offshore production to continue if the export route becomes unavailable.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Export to the oil refinery is either by pipeline or tanker.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Onshore gas terminals may have facilities for removal of liquids from the incoming gas stream.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] Gas treatment processes may include glycol dehydration, gas sweetening, hydrocarbon dew-point control and gas compression before gas distribution to users.
[src:iso-15926/process-plant] In addition to production and gas and oil treatment systems a range of ancillary, support and utility systems are provided to support production and occupation of an offshore installation.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In industry, **product lifecycle management** (**PLM**) is the process of managing the entire lifecycle of a product from its inception through the engineering, design, and manufacture, as well as the service and disposal of manufactured products.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PLM integrates people, data, processes, and business systems and provides a product information backbone for companies and their extended enterprises.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The inspiration for the burgeoning business process now known as PLM came from American Motors Corporation (AMC).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The automaker was looking for a way to speed up its product development process to compete better against its larger competitors in 1985, according to François Castaing, Vice President for Product Engineering and Development.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The first part in its quest for faster product development was computer-aided design (CAD) software system that made engineers more productive.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The second part of this effort was the new communication system that allowed conflicts to be resolved faster, as well as reducing costly engineering changes because all drawings and documents were in a central database.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The product data management was so effective that after Chrysler purchased AMC, the system was expanded throughout the enterprise connecting everyone involved in designing and building products.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] While an early adopter of PLM technology, Chrysler was able to become the auto industry's lowest-cost producer, recording development costs that were half of the industry average by the mid-1990s.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PLM systems help organizations cope with the increasing complexity and engineering challenges of developing new products for the global competitive markets.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product lifecycle management (PLM) should be distinguished from 'product life-cycle management (marketing)' (PLCM).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PLM describes a product's engineering aspect, from managing its descriptions and properties through its development and useful life.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In contrast, PLCM refers to the commercial management of a product's life in the business market concerning costs and sales measures.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product lifecycle management can be considered one of the four cornerstones of a manufacturing corporation's information technology structure.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] One form of PLM is called people-centric PLM.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] While traditional PLM tools have been deployed only on or during the release phase, people-centric PLM targets the design phase.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This broader reach has resulted in the extension of PLM into closed-loop lifecycle management (CL2M).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product and portfolio management2 (PPM) are focused on managing resource allocation, tracking progress, planning for new product development projects that are in process (or in a holding status).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Portfolio management is a tool that assists management in tracking progress on new products and making trade-off decisions when allocating scarce resources.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product design (CAx) is the process of creating a new product to be sold by a business to its customers.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Manufacturing process management (MPM) is a collection of technologies and methods used to define how products are to be manufactured.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product data management (PDM) is focused on capturing and maintaining information on products and/or services through their development and useful life.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Change management is an important part of PDM/PLM.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The core of PLM (product lifecycle management) is the creation and central management of all product data and the technology used to access this information and knowledge.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PLM as a discipline emerged from tools such as CAD, CAM and PDM, but can be viewed as the integration of these tools with methods, people and the processes through all stages of a product's life.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It is not just about software technology but is also a business strategy.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] For simplicity, the stages described are shown in a traditional sequential engineering workflow.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The reality is however more complex, people and departments cannot perform their tasks in isolation and one activity cannot simply finish, and the next activity start.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Design is an iterative process, often designs need to be modified due to manufacturing constraints or conflicting requirements.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Whether a customer order fits into the timeline depends on the industry type and whether the products are, for example, built to order, engineered to order, or assembled to order.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Many software solutions have been developed to organize and integrate the different phases of a product's lifecycle.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PLM should not be considered as a single software product, but as a collection of software tools and working methods integrated to address single stages of the lifecycle, connect different tasks, or manage the whole process.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Some software providers cover the whole PLM range, while others have a single niche application.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Some applications can span many fields of PLM with different modules within the same data model.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] An overview of the fields within PLM is covered here.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The simple classifications do not always fit exactly; many areas overlap, and many software products cover more than one area or do not fit easily into one category.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] One of the main goals of PLM is to collect knowledge that can be reused for other projects and to coordinate the simultaneous concurrent development of many products.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It is about business processes, people, and methods as much as software application solutions.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Although PLM is mainly associated with engineering tasks, it also involves marketing activities such as product portfolio management (PPM), particularly concerning new product development (NPD).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Each industry has several life-cycle models to consider, but most are relatively similar.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The first stage is the definition of the product requirements based on customer, company, market, and regulatory bodies' viewpoints.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] From this specification, the product's major technical parameters can be defined.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In parallel, the initial concept design work is performed, defining the aesthetics of the product together with its main functional aspects.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Many different media are used for these processes, from pencil and paper to clay models to 3D CAID computer-aided industrial design software.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In some concepts, the investment of resources into research or analysis of options may be included in the conception phase – e.g., bringing the technology to a level of maturity sufficient to move to the next phase.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] However, life-cycle engineering is iterative.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It is always possible that something does not work well in any phase enough to back up into a prior phase – perhaps back to conception or research.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The new product development process phase collects and evaluates market and technical risks by measuring the KPI and scoring model.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This step is where the detailed design and development of the product's form starts, progressing to prototype testing, from pilot release to full product launch.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It can also involve redesign and ramping to improve existing products and planned obsolescence.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] CAD is the primary tool used for design and development.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This can be simple 2D drawing/drafting or 3D parametric feature-based solid/surface modeling.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Such software may include Hybrid Modeling, Reverse Engineering, KBE (knowledge-based engineering), NDT (Nondestructive testing), and Assembly construction.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This step covers many engineering disciplines, including mechanical, electrical, electronic, software (embedded), and domain-specific, such as architectural, aerospace, and automotive.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Along with creating geometry, the components and product assemblies are analyzed.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Simulation, validation, and optimization tasks are carried out using CAE (computer-aided engineering) software, either integrated into the CAD package or stand-alone.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] These are used to perform tasks such as Stress analysis, FEA (finite element analysis), kinematics, computational fluid dynamics (CFD), and mechanical event simulation (MES).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] CAQ (computer-aided quality) is used for tasks such as Dimensional tolerance (engineering) analysis.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Another task performed at this stage is sourcing bought-out components, possibly with the aid of procurement systems.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Once the design of the product's components is complete, the method of manufacturing is defined.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This includes CAD tasks such as tool design; including the creation of CNC machining instructions for the product's parts as well as the creation of specific tools to manufacture those parts, using integrated or separate CAM (computer-aided manufacturing) software.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This will also involve analysis tools for process simulation of operations such as casting, molding, and die-press forming.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Once the manufacturing method has been identified, CPM comes into play.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This involves CAPE (computer-aided production engineering) or CAP/CAPP (computer-aided production planning) tools for carrying out factory, plant and facility layout, and production simulation e.g. press-line simulation, industrial ergonomics, as well as tool selection management.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] After components are manufactured, their geometrical form and size can be checked against the original CAD data with the use of computer-aided inspection equipment and software.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Parallel to the engineering tasks, sales product configuration, and marketing documentation work takes place.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This could include transferring engineering data (geometry and part list data) to a web-based sales configurator and other desktop publishing systems.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Another phase of the lifecycle involves managing "in-service" information.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This can include providing customers and service engineers with the support and information required for repair and maintenance, as well as waste management or recycling.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This can involve the use of tools such as Maintenance, Repair, and Overhaul Management (MRO) software.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] An effective service consideration begins during and even prior to product design as an integral part of product lifecycle management.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Service Lifecycle Management (SLM) has critical touchpoints at all phases of the product lifecycle that must be considered.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Connecting and enriching a common digital thread will provide enhanced visibility across functions, improve data quality, and minimize costly delays and rework.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] There is an end-of-life to every product.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Whether it be the disposal or destruction of material objects or information, this needs to be carefully considered since it may be legislated and hence not free from ramifications.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This modernization approach often extends the product lifecycle and delays end-of-life disposal.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] None of the above phases should be considered as isolated.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In reality, a project does not run sequentially or separated from other product development projects, with information flowing between different people and systems.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] A major part of PLM is the coordination and management of product definition data.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This includes managing engineering changes and release status of components; configuration product variations; document management; planning project resources as well as timescale and risk assessment.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] For these tasks data of a graphical, textual, and meta nature – such as product bills of materials (BOMs) – needs to be managed.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] These systems may also be linked to other corporate systems such as SCM, CRM, and ERP.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Associated with these systems are project management systems for project/program planning.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This central role is covered by numerous collaborative product development tools that run throughout the whole lifecycle and across organizations.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This requires many technology tools in the areas of conferencing, data sharing, and data translation.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This specialized field is referred to as product visualization which includes technologies such as DMU (digital mock-up), immersive virtual digital prototyping (virtual reality), and photo-realistic imaging.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The broad array of solutions that make up the tools used within a PLM solution-set (e.g., CAD, CAM, CAx) were initially used by dedicated practitioners who invested time and effort to gain the required skills.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Designers and engineers produced excellent results with CAD systems, manufacturing engineers became highly skilled CAM users, while analysts, administrators, and managers fully mastered their support technologies.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] However, achieving the full advantages of PLM requires the participation of many people of various skills from throughout an extended enterprise, each requiring the ability to access and operate on the inputs and output of other participants.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Despite the increased ease of use of PLM tools, cross-training all personnel on the entire PLM tool-set has not proven to be practical.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Now, however, advances are being made to address ease of use for all participants within the PLM arena.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] One such advance is the availability of "role" specific user interfaces.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Through tailorable user interfaces (UIs), the commands that are presented to users are appropriate to their function and expertise.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Feature-based CAD systems have allowed simultaneous work on the 3D solid model and the 2D drawing by means of two separate files, with the drawing looking at the data in the model; when the model changes the drawing will associatively update.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Some CAD packages also allow associative copying of geometry between files.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This allows, for example, the copying of a part design into the files used by the tooling designer.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The manufacturing engineer can then start work on tools before the final design freeze; when a design changes size or shape the tool geometry will then update.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Concurrent engineering also has the added benefit of providing better and more immediate communication between departments, reducing the chance of costly, late design changes.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It adopts a problem-prevention method as compared to the problem-solving and re-designing method of traditional sequential engineering.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Bottom-up design (CAD-centric) occurs where the definition of 3D models of a product starts with the construction of individual components.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] These are then virtually brought together in sub-assemblies of more than one level until the full product is digitally defined.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This is sometimes known as the "review structure" which shows what the product will look like.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Bottom-up design tends to focus on the capabilities of available real-world physical technology, implementing those solutions to which this technology is most suited.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] When these bottom-up solutions have real-world value, bottom-up design can be much more efficient than top-down design.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The risk of bottom-up design is that it very efficiently provides solutions to low-value problems.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Top-down design is focused on high-level functional requirements, with relatively less focus on existing implementation technology.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] A top-level spec is repeatedly decomposed into lower-level structures and specifications until the physical implementation layer is reached.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The positive value of top-down design is that it preserves a focus on the optimum solution requirements.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] A part-centric top-down design may eliminate some of the risks of top-down design.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This starts with a layout model, often a simple 2D sketch defining basic sizes and some major defining parameters, which may include some industrial design elements.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Geometry from this is associatively copied down to the next level, which represents different subsystems of the product.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The geometry in the sub-systems is then used to define more detail in the levels below.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Depending on the complexity of the product, a number of levels of this assembly are created until the basic definition of components can be identified, such as position and principal dimensions.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This information is then associatively copied to component files.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In these files the components are detailed; this is where the classic bottom-up assembly starts.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The top-down assembly is sometimes known as a "control structure".
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] If a single file is used to define the layout and parameters for the review structure it is often known as a skeleton file.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Defense engineering traditionally develops the product structure from the top down.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The system engineering process prescribes a functional decomposition of requirements and then the physical allocation of product structure to the functions.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This top down approach would normally have lower levels of the product structure developed from CAD data as a bottom-up structure or design.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Both-ends-against-the-middle (BEATM) design is a design process that endeavors to combine the best features of top-down design, and bottom-up design into one process.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] A BEATM design process flow may begin with an emergent technology that suggests solutions that may have value, or it may begin with a top-down view of an important problem that needs a solution.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In either case, the key attribute of BEATM design methodology is to immediately focus on both ends of the design process flow: a top-down view of the solution requirements, and a bottom-up view of the available technology which may offer the promise of an efficient solution.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The BEATM design process proceeds from both ends in search of an optimum merging somewhere between the top-down requirements, and bottom-up efficient implementation.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] In this fashion, BEATM has been shown to genuinely offer the best of both methodologies.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Indeed, some of the best success stories from either top-down or bottom-up have been successful because of an intuitive, yet unconscious use of the BEATM methodology.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] When employed consciously, BEATM offers even more powerful advantages.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Front loading is taking top-down design to the next stage.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The complete control structure and review structure, as well as downstream data such as drawings, tooling development, and CAM models, are constructed before the product has been defined or a project kick-off has been authorized.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] These assemblies of files constitute a template from which a family of products can be constructed.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] When the decision has been made to go with a new product, the parameters of the product are entered into the template model, and all the associated data is updated.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Obviously, predefined associative models will not be able to predict all possibilities and will require additional work.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The main principle is that a lot of the experimental/investigative work has already been completed.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] A lot of knowledge is built into these templates to be reused on new products.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This does require additional resources "up front" but can drastically reduce the time between project kick-off and launch.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Such methods do however require organizational changes, as considerable engineering efforts are moved into "offline" development departments.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] It can be seen as an analogy to creating a concept car to test new technology for future products, but in this case, the work is directly used for the next product generation.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Individual components cannot be constructed in isolation.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] CAD and CAID models of components are created within the context of some or all of the other components within the product being developed.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This is achieved using assembly modelling techniques.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The geometry of other components can be seen and referenced within the CAD tool being used.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The other referenced components may or may not have been created using the same CAD tool, with their geometry being translated from other collaborative product development (CPD) formats.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Some assembly checking such as DMU is also carried out using product visualization software.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Product and process lifecycle management **(PPLM)** is an alternate genre of PLM in which the process by which the product is made is just as important as the product itself.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Typically, this is the life sciences and advanced specialty chemicals markets.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The process behind the manufacture of a given compound is a key element of the regulatory filing for a new drug application.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] As such, PPLM seeks to manage information around the development of the process in a similar fashion that baseline PLM talks about managing information around the development of the product.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] One variant of PPLM implementations are Process Development Execution Systems (PDES).
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] They typically implement the whole development cycle of high-tech manufacturing technology developments, from initial conception, through development, and into manufacture.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] PDES integrates people with different backgrounds from potentially different legal entities, data, information and knowledge, and business processes.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] After the Great Recession, PLM investments from 2010 onwards showed a higher growth rate than most general IT spending.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] Total spending on PLM software and services was estimated in 2020 to be $26 billion a year, with an estimated compound annual growth rate of 7.2% from 2021 to 2028.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] This was expected to be driven by a demand for software solutions for management functions, such as change, cost, compliance, data, and governance management.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The relation between these five objects can be presented as a pyramid with its tip associated with the lowest Cost, highest Productivity, highest Quality, most Flexibility, and greatest Sustainability.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The points inside of this pyramid are associated with different combinations of five criteria.
[src:iso-15926/product-lifecycle] The tip of the pyramid represents an ideal (but likely highly unfeasible) system whereas the base of the pyramid represents the worst system possible.
